INSERT INTO `messages` VALUES (39, 447, 0, 409, 'Upgrade Ideas Thread', 'QGUIDE ob', '2005-09-07 21:58:00', 0, 'SUBJ: Upgrade Ideas Thread             FROM: QGUIDE ob   09/07/2005 S# 447\nThought I''d start a thread for upgrade ideas.  I know Jim''s focus is the primary system functions, but I thought it would never hurt to fill his head with neat ideas while he''s hurling code.  Here''s an idea to kick off the thread:\n\nuser text macros in people connection.\neach user could set //1 //2 //3 //4\nto their own lines of text while they are logged on.  Users could repeat their favorite welcome message, etc whenever they wanted by using their own private // command.\n\nJeff\n ');
INSERT INTO `messages` VALUES (40, 448, 446, 409, 'Games', 'Thea1ien', '2005-09-08 06:53:21', 0, 'SUBJ: Games                            FROM: Thea1ien    09/08/2005 S# 448\nI think Pina had some problem as of\nlast night. I do know at least, that I\ncannot play games from my 128D setup,\nand suspect it is because of the 2400 patch. However I also figure this is not the patch''s fault...I assume if I had patched a disk and used it on the old Qlink, games worked. If so, then it just means something to figure out and fix on the server side. I guess we will need to give jim a chance to figure it out sometime.\nThere was alot going on, yesterday was still the first day of games support, so this is probably only a matter of time. But on the first day, can''t expect jim to catch and fix everything of course.\nI''ll try to catch him when he has more time and see if he can figure out what is happening on his end that causes my 128D not to play games yet.\n ');
INSERT INTO `messages` VALUES (41, 449, 446, 409, 'Games', 'QGUIDE ob', '2005-09-08 12:13:27', 0, 'SUBJ: Games                            FROM: QGUIDE ob   09/08/2005 S# 449\nFor those who can''t remember those\nkeys from twenty years ago...\nF2 seems to be key in switching from chatroom mode to game turn mode.\nAfraid I sprewed a lot of a,d,w,x keys into People Connection figuring that out. :)    Guess we should start using private/public rooms away from the lobby for gaming.  Although, personally I like being about to play and chat at the same time.  QuantumLink was so far ahead of its time.\n\nJeff\n ');
INSERT INTO `messages` VALUES (42, 452, 0, 409, 'CMD HD Manual', 'Thea1ien', '2005-09-09 07:48:58', 3, 'SUBJ: CMD HD Manual                    FROM: Thea1ien    09/09/2005 S# 452\nI''m trying to find someone that has an older CMD HD''s users guide. I need to know what is contained in chapter 7 (starts at page 7-1) in the original guides. Newer guides had these pages blanked, because Qlink was no more. I believe I have all the files that were supplied (I used to have an older drive and the manual but since got rid of it many years back after I got my 1gig unit).\nIf anyone has this, please either post it here or at least qmail me and let me know. I think the information could be more helpful posted here though for all to see. Might prove to be helpful.\nThanks\n ');
INSERT INTO `messages` VALUES (43, 453, 452, 409, 'I have it.', 'RaymondD2', '2005-09-09 08:33:01', 0, 'SUBJ: I have it.                       FROM: RaymondD2   09/09/2005 S# 453\nI will try to copy it by typing it here.\n\nSection 7\n\nUsing Q-Link\n\nAbout Q-Link\n----------------------------------------\nQ-Link is an inexpensive nation-wide electronic network service provided by\nQuantum Computer Services for use by Commodore computer owners.\nAmong other things, Q-Link provides its members with the following services:\n\n* INFORMATION - News, online encyclopedia, seminars, workshops\n\n* SOFTWARE - One of the largest collections of Commodore programs\n\n* ONLINE GAMES - Play by yourself and with other members\n\n* CHAT AREAS - Where you can converse with other users and friends\n\n*SUPPORT - A direct link with CMD and other companies\n\n* MESSAGES - Classified ads and special interest areas\n\nThere are many, many more features on Q-Link. If you are not already\nreceiving the benefits of a low cost membership on this service exclusively\nfor Commodore users, sign on by using the provided software. There''s a lot\nof information just waiting for you, and it''s also one of the fastest ways to\nget help or advice about using you CMD products.\n\nSigning on to Q-Link\n---------------------------------------+\nIf you have never been on Q-Link before, you will need some information.\nThis information is provided in the Q-Link Kit which accompanied your\nHD. If the Q-Link package was not provided for some reason, contact Quantum Computer Customer Service at 1-703-883-0788, or if you are\ncalling from Canada 1-703-883-0789.\n\nEverything you need to know to log-on for the first time is described in the\nQ-Link brochure. However, make note of the following differences given\nbelow. If you have problems logging on for the first time, contact Q-Link\nat 1-800-392-8200 (US) or 1-703-883-0789 (Canada).\n\nThe CMD/Q-LInk System Disk: The software contained on this disk is already located in partition 6 of your HD. You can (and should) use\nMCOPY to make a backup of this software. ');
INSERT INTO `messages` VALUES (44, 454, 452, 409, 'Page 7-2', 'RaymondD2', '2005-09-09 08:46:44', 0, 'SUBJ: Page 7-2                         FROM: RaymondD2   09/09/2005 S# 454\nLoading Q-Link from the HD\n\nThere are some differences to note when loading the special HD-compatible\nQ-Link software from your HD. Follow these steps when loading the\nQ-Link software from the HD for the fist time:\n\n1. Turn the power on to your monitor, CMD HD, and computer. If you\nare using a Commodore 128 or 128D, hold down the COMMODORE\nkey while turning on the computer so that it will be in 64 Mode.\n\n2 Partition 1 contains a program called BOOTQ. Type the following{\n\n     LOAD"1//:BOOTQ",12\n\nand press the RETURN key. If you have changed your HD''s default\ndevice number, substitute the ''12'' at the end of the LOAD command\nwith the correct device number.\n\n3.  When the READY prompt appears, type:\n\n   RUN\n\nand press the RETURN key.\n\nIf the Q-Link software was not pre-installed on your HD\n\nIf the special HD version of the Q-Link software did not come pre-installed\non your HD, copy it to a 1541 Emulation Mode partition by using MCOPY. After you have copied the Q-Link disk to the HD, turn your\ncomputer off and back on again. Change to the partition where you placed\nthe Q-Link software by using the CP command. Next, press the SWAP 8 button, and type:\n\n  LOAD"*",8,1\n\nand press the RETURN key.\n\nIf you can, use partition 6 for the Q-Link software. You may then copy the BOOTQ program from the HD UTILITIES disk into partition 1 using\nFCOPY. This will allow you to use the same instructions as those who\nreceived the Q-Link software already installed on the HD.\n\n---------------------------------------\nNote: If you have problems with disk errors on the HD or the CMD/Q-\nLink System disk provided with th HD, contact CMD for assistance.\nCMD, not Quantum Computer, is responsible for any software supplied\non or with the HD.\n---------------------------------------                                    ');
INSERT INTO `messages` VALUES (45, 455, 452, 409, 'Page 7-3', 'RaymondD2', '2005-09-09 08:58:40', 0, 'SUBJ: Page 7-3                         FROM: RaymondD2   09/09/2005 S# 455\nQ-Link Members and Backups\n----------------------------------------\nIf yo are already a member of Q-Link, use the program located on your HD\nUTILITIES disk call XFER QDATA. This program will allow you to transfer your Q+Link sign+on data to the HD. Upgraders: this should be done\nafter placing a copy of the Q-Link system disk or to a floppy disk copy of the Q-Link\npartition (created with MCOPY).\n\nUploading, Downloading, and Other Disks\n----------------------------------------\nYou may use other partitions on your HD for uploading and downloading\nsoftware while connected to Q-Link. To do this, study the instructions for\nusing FPPS Mode, located else where in this manual. When you wish to\nupload or download a file, move to the appropriate partition using FPPS\nMode. This should be done just prior to selecting the ''Upload a file'' or\n''Download this file'' from the Q-Link menu. You should only use 1541\nEmulation Mode partitions for doing this, unless you have created or are\nusing a patch for one of the other partition types. The patch for 1581 disk\ndrives located on Q-Link will work with 1581 partitions. The 1541SUB\nprogram can also create a suitable patch in an empty Native Mode partition.\n\nYou may also use CASINO and SUPER-Q with your HD. These should be\nplaced in 1541 Emulation Mode partitions, and can be accessed with the\nFPPS Mode as well.\n\nCLUB CARIBE and PUZZLER MAY NOT BE USIED ON THE HD. It is possible\nto upload, download, or use CASINO< PUZZLER OR SUPER-Q on a floppy\ndisk by using the SWAP 8 button. This will cause the floppy disk on your\nsystem which is normally device number 8 to be used.\n\nNote: Be sure to change back to your main Q-Link partition, or SWAP 8 back to the HD (if you have SWAPped to another drive) whenever the\nsystem requests you to insert your Q-Link disk.\n\nTo use CLUB CARIBE it will be necessary to boot with a standard Q-Link boot disk on a floppy disk drive, and may also require disconnecting the HD\nand other devices attached to the serial bus. For further information on using CLUB CARIBE, see the Club Caribe Users Guide. ');
INSERT INTO `messages` VALUES (46, 456, 446, 409, 'Games', 'Pinacolada', '2005-09-09 12:47:34', 0, 'SUBJ: Games                            FROM: Pinacolada  09/09/2005 S# 456\nThe games are pretty neat. Well programmed... and if Sea Strike and Hangman are in BASIC, we should be able to dissect them and maybe program new games. :)\n ');
INSERT INTO `messages` VALUES (47, 457, 0, 409, 'Boot Qlink off other drive types', 'Thea1ien', '2005-09-09 14:09:20', 1, 'SUBJ: Boot Qlink off other drive types FROM: Thea1ien    09/09/2005 S# 457\nOk. For awhile now it has been known that Raymond Day has an old qlink disk on a 1581 disk that will load up and run, but been unable to figure out how he did it.\nI was playing around and actually figured it out in winvice easily.\n\nThe linker program included with the 2400 baud patcher. While I was looking at the code, I could see it puts some initial data statements into memory and at times runs ML. I looked further into the basic lines and noticed that it checks initially track 18, sector 1 (a 1541 disk dir track, start of the filename data). Then if it fails that check, there is another attempt, but this time track 40, sector 3 (Aha! a 1581 disk, same deal..file data start).\n\nI ran the linker program on a 1581 disk in winvice (after copying all files on the qdisk) and it patched them. I also used the xfer qdata program (I had to rem the section that tries to change partitions, as this program was only designed for a 1541 to HD unit).\nFor some reason, the first time I ran it, I noticed in winvice the 1581 stayed in track 40, and I dont think actually wrote anything. However I ran it again immediatly after and the 2nd time it changed the 1581 to track 18, sector 15 which is the userdata area.\n\nI then tried to boot the 1581 disk, and it loaded up and let me log on!!!\n\nThis is great! It still needs some issues looked into though. Maybe someone with alittle more drive know-how can assist easier in this part.\n\nOn the 1541 drive, the user data should be safe from overwrites by adding files to the disk later. However that same track and sector on  the 1581 and any other drive is normally for file data.\n\nMaybe someone can write a program to create a "fake" file in the dir list, and link it to that location of the disk? It would make it easier. The BAM would have to be changed as well.\n\nI also tried this on my FD-2000 drive using a full native HD formatted disk, however the linker fails on the NTK file, and the qlink disk fails to load. Obviously someone also needs to look at that file and try to figure it out, so it will support other drives. It would be nice. ');
INSERT INTO `messages` VALUES (48, 458, 0, 409, 'A MOSTEK DC-10 RS232 works', 'Ray Day', '2005-09-10 11:02:11', 0, 'SUBJ: A MOSTEK DC-10 RS232 works       FROM: Ray Day     09/10/2005 S# 458\nI was putting all my 1541 disk back that I got down to find the Q-Link buffer files. My room was a mess. They are all back on the self now.\n\nBut wile putting them back I found a old RS232 board. It''s small. The name on it is MOSTEK DC-10. It has 4 dip switchs on it. I don''t know what they do but I put my 3 wire home made cable on it 25 male to 25 male D-SUB. It works. I am on it now like that.\n\nI had to run XFER QDATA on my 1541 disk that I used to boot here. Because I changed the port number when Jim was testing and I had to use a new name. Then I could not get back on it would say to call Q-Link. So I copied my QDATA from the hard drive and I last used that as the name Ray Day. So I am on here now like that. That XFER QDATA works good. It''s on a older CMD HD Utilities disk. Mine says Copyright (c) 1990 on it.\n\n-Raymond Day ');
INSERT INTO `messages` VALUES (49, 459, 0, 409, 'Chess and Reversi', 'MetalMage', '2005-09-11 04:09:52', 2, 'SUBJ: Chess and Reversi                FROM: MetalMage   09/11/2005 S# 459\nThanks to The A1ien and Jeff for their contribution mirror.petscii.com/qlink\n\nI downloaded the qlinkdisks.zip file and extracted the files\n\nqlinkgamesd1.d64\nqlinkgamesd2.d64\n\ninto the directory where QuantumLink.d64 resides.\n\nI typed LOAD"ADDGAMES",8,1 and followed the instructions on the screen from there on to add CHESS on disk 1 and REVERSI on disk 2 to my Q-Link disk.\n\nChristianL and I tested these games and they worked great.  Chess does NOT check if a move is valid, so be careful!  There is a take back last move option F7/MORE... which lets you fix a bad/illegal move.\n\nREVERSI does check if a move is valid.  However, it does not NOTIFY the players who WON the game.  You must choose to END the game after someone wins to exit it.\n\nThe games work, but you have to SWAP disks, and when you are done playing, SWAP your Q-Link disk back to return to People Connection''s Lobby.\n\nI am even more impressed Jim!  Great job!  So, the games are the clients and the server just blindly sends/receives packets during game play?  This means that you could DESIGN new games could you not?  Are the games in BASIC code or ML?\n\nWinVICE 1.16 is what I have been using to test the games.  Is there a fix coming for those of us who connect at 2400 baud using the 0011/DSC patch files for the SL-232 compatible cart?\n\nI even played a game of Hangman.  Have not tried Sea Strike yet, but I am sure it is working fairly well.\n\nMetalMage\nforgottenrealmsbbs.org\n ');
INSERT INTO `messages` VALUES (50, 460, 459, 409, 'chess', 'Thea1ien', '2005-09-11 06:53:08', 0, 'SUBJ: chess                            FROM: Thea1ien    09/11/2005 S# 460\nI know for a fact that the chess game on original qlink did the same thing. Unless there was something with qlink before the system issues (which was before my time on Q), I assume the chess was built this way and just lacked illegal move checking...\n ');
INSERT INTO `messages` VALUES (51, 461, 459, 409, 'New Games', 'QGUIDE ob', '2005-09-11 12:34:57', 0, 'SUBJ: New Games                        FROM: QGUIDE ob   09/11/2005 S# 461\nJeff send me some basic listings for both Seastrike and Hangman.  It does indeed appear that new games could be created for People Connection!  IIUC, it looks like we could extract the PC connection support. (I suspect is running as ML in the background) and write new games around it in basic.\nI''ve started tracking through the listings to get an understanding of how it works.  I''m thinking of writting a  TRIVIA host interface.  The files are located for your viewing pleasure at http://mirror.petscii.com/qlink\n\nJeff\n    ');
INSERT INTO `messages` VALUES (52, 462, 0, 409, 'Final days of Qlink 1', 'QGUIDE ob', '2005-09-11 12:45:04', 3, 'SUBJ: Final days of Qlink 1            FROM: QGUIDE ob   09/11/2005 S# 462\n...designed the origina ''failed'' Matrix, and the current ''successful'' one.  The first Matrix failed because it was too perfect, A virtual paradise, a utopia for humans.  Unfortunately, humans were not accustomed to living in a perfect world...."\n\nI was a Qlinker during it''s golden era. As I understand toward the end, Qlink began to fall apart, either by extended use, or neglect, or resources being reallocated to the ''new'' project. \n\nThose of you who were there at the end. Was it really falling apart at seams?  In reading Raymonds message capture, it looks like this was a progressive fall toward the end.  What was happening at the end?\n\nJeff\n ');
INSERT INTO `messages` VALUES (53, 463, 462, 409, 'Hmmm', 'MetalMage', '2005-09-11 22:32:08', 0, 'SUBJ: Hmmm                             FROM: MetalMage   09/11/2005 S# 463\nWell.  I remember a program called ScrewLink and sessions of P2P file transfers with hackers, crackers, and phreakers.  People were always trying to set up bogus accounts with CC#s they obtained... no one wanted to PAY but everyone was willing to PLAY.\n\nThis was pre-Casino and even pre-Habitat I believe, since I was running 6485 BBS and moved to C-Net 10.0 after meeting FREEZE, Bobby Griggs, another C-Net SysOp in the PC.  We chatted and played games.  I was new to the scene.  He taught me how to phreak and hack and I was hooked.  I left the Q-Link scene and entered the BBS scene.  Back in the day, only RIBIT BBS, and BBS Construction Set were the programs other than 6485 BBS people used to run a BBS in the local area.  I was the first to bring C-Net to the area, which just blew away all of the other boards that were running.\n\nLD was not a problem for me in those days.  <whistle>\n\nEventually, the US Sprint special investigations and the FBI investigated me with a dial-number recorder and visited my home when Operation Sundevil was in full-swing.  They threatened, scared me, but they just copied the disks and took my user listing.  One even signed on as AGENT for his login name.  LOL!\n\nMy dad bought me a 300 baud modem and we signed up for Q-Link together.  He thought it was pretty cool.  At 15, you cannot appreciate a service like that as we can now... specially as developers and IT people...\n\nQ-Link like all cool things, just got overrun by idiots as the AOL mentality to earn $$$ from online users manifested itself.  My guess.\n\nThe 64 was not as sexy as a PC in 94 with the PCBoard, Wildcat!, etc. systems and IMAGINATION!\n\nAnyone remember what service IMAGINATION was for??? Multiplayer gaming... on a PC I believe.\n\nAOL... that is what killed Q-Link.\n\nThe PC is what killed the 64/128.  Piracy and protection.  No affordable hard drive and software that could be installed on it off the shelves.\n\nOtherwise, Commodore might have been up there with IBM and Micro$oft, eh?\n\nOf course, the C-65 didn''t help.\n\n  -- METAL MAGE\n  ');
INSERT INTO `messages` VALUES (54, 464, 0, 409, 'MySQL/PHP Front End', 'MetalMage', '2005-09-11 22:47:52', 3, 'SUBJ: MySQL/PHP Front End              FROM: MetalMage   09/11/2005 S# 464\nI have been invited by Jim to explore the possibilities of developing the admin module for Q-Link as a MySQL/PHP powered web application.  That is my specialty, content management systems.\n\nI would need an SQL dump of the database for MySQL, so I could use it as dummy data for the development phase of this project.\n\nCurrently, my MySQL server is set up as localhost with ODBC hooks.  IndigoPerl, Apache distro for Windows servers supports PHP 4 and PERL 5.\n\nHowever, I am sure that PHP DB scripts can be edited to connect to remote MySQL databases via the URL info, user, and password.  If this is so, the implementation of such a project would be easy.  Develop it to work on my side to add/edit/delete users, messages, etc., and then give it to Jeff to run on quantum-link.org.\n\nI would be interested and very honored to help out where I can.\n\nI know Java, servers, sockets, MySQL databases, C#.NET, PHP, PERL, BASIC 2.0, and probably stuff I forgot I even knew... but I know I could contribute my skills and talents if there is room among the giants here...\n\nCan''t use Linux to save my life, but I am a true Windiot developer... used to do some major development Java projects... Oracle9i, SQLJ, Swing JFC, stuff like that.  Even wrote a C# web application server, that had an ActiveX CommPort RS-232 library for a smart home project.  Web-based admin for EDT lighting dimmer switches, and a digital I/O controller via USB for turning relays on/off and sensing current flow for remote controlled/monitored electrical outlets.\n\nIt was a fun project.  I wrote my own StringTokenizer to process HTML POSTED form data using hidden tags... and the server would generate the pages HTML/Javascript code in real-time... to create the GUI using HTML form elements.\n\nWrote an online casino with JDBC for Foxpro... animated GUI with images, sounds, sockets... and some other IT projects...\n\nQ-Link would be fun.  I think I could comprehend some of Jim''s madness.\n\n-- METAL MAGE --\n   ');
INSERT INTO `messages` VALUES (55, 465, 462, 409, 'From what I remember', 'RaymondD2', '2005-09-12 04:32:00', 0, 'SUBJ: From what I remember             FROM: RaymondD2   09/12/2005 S# 465\nI am on VICE now. I will copy this track 18 sector 15 to my real Q-Link disk that I mosly get on with because this name RaymondD2 was the last one I used on Q-Link.\n\nBut in the last days I used a disk from a friend that had lots of + time left over. I remember as RaymondD2 I quit Q-link because near the end it was getting so bad. They just deleted files for AOL and if I remember right some messages too. A lot of the text that went with files was gone too. You could complan to Q-link to no end! They just left it like on auto pilot about the last year! Messing it up more and more using the same server for AOL.\n\nI have lots of saved Q-Link e-mail to me about REU upgrades back when I was RaymondD2.\n\nWhen I got on as WiggleWorm with Leonette''s Q-Link Boot disk I mostly started to download as meny stereo SID''s as I could at 2400 baud. I never even got it all. There was a lot. But I guess people together my of got it all and with time I think this new Q-Link can get at lest all the files back but not the descriptions and comments of each file :(\n\nI just mostly remember to hate AOL how they just like abandoned Q-Link with no care of all the good data that was lost!\n\nI can see if something replaces PC how AOL would do the same with it''s service as they did with Q-Link.\n\nWhen I was on as RaymondD2 I remember going over a friends house taking my commodore set up maybe 8am to some times mid night we would get on Q-Link and play the name that tune game with Super Q. It was so fun to get the names of the SID songs before others would. That gave me Q-pons that I could use to get more + time. I just could not aford going a lot over my $9.95 per month and they gave you 1 hour + time with that $9.95.\n\nJust typeing a message like this was + time! I remember I think it was with Super Q. I could wight things like this and load it from a file! That was nice and fast!\n\nThere are lots of things I don''t remember but come back a little as I look for old text messages I saved. Like I know of the pass word was on track 18 sector 15 and leaving Super Q wrong could mess that up.\n\nI was on Q-link as WiggleWorm in about the last 4 hours before mid night when they trun it off for good. I remember I did something that I know my mess up my Q-Link disk and that messed it up so it comes back now with "A disk error has occurred." I think it was only for the 1581 Q-Link boot disk that this error my happend. I never fixed it in time to be on at the very end. I saved some + time too to be on at the very end. ');
