INSERT INTO `messages` VALUES (57, 467, 464, 409, 'Re: SQL Frontend', 'Madcrow', '2005-09-12 12:52:57', 0, 'SUBJ: Re: SQL Frontend                 FROM: Madcrow     09/12/2005 S# 467\nThat sounds like a good idea... It would make it much easier to check in when away from a C64 or a computer that one can put VICE onto...\n\nMadcrow (Mike) ');
INSERT INTO `messages` VALUES (58, 468, 464, 409, 'No', 'MetalMage', '2005-09-12 13:27:55', 0, 'SUBJ: No                               FROM: MetalMage   09/12/2005 S# 468\nIt would be for the QADMINs to add new menu content to Q-Link, such as articles, files, etc.\n\nSince MySQL is the RDBMS Jim used to save persistant data in a stateless environment, such as the web or a network, PHP scripts are able to access, display, and manipulate the data in the clink database schema for the Q-Link Server.\n\nI have a skeleton of the admin panel up and running, which does nothing so far, but will eventually as soon as Jim can explain to me what he wants it to do and how it must work.\n\nvisit www.w3productions.com/qlink/admin\n\nlogin using test and test for login/pw.\n\nAdd Content, will display the current toc records, and will have HTML form buttons with hidden tags to store data for the FORM button.\n\nIn a perfect world, you will click on the ADD: {CATAGORY} button link... and then the screen to add that TYPE of content will be displayed.\n\nYou will select the options available from a drop down menu box, like NO CHARGE, or PREMIUM, and use the TEXT AREA editor to type in/paste story content.  SUBMIT will send the data to the MySQL database tables, thus making the new content LIVE! on the server.\n\nJim uses phpMyAdmin, a web-driven interface powered by PHP scripts, to update the records/tables in the database by hand.  The admin panel would provide an easier and straight-forward way to do this instead.\n\nUsing the admin panel, other QADMINs could post content, as Jim develops the server code.\n\n  - METAL MAGE -\n  dave@w3productions.com\n  w3productions.com\n  forgottenrealmsbbs.org\n ');
INSERT INTO `messages` VALUES (59, 469, 0, 409, 'GAME DEVELOPMENT', 'MetalMage', '2005-09-12 13:43:48', 0, 'SUBJ: GAME DEVELOPMENT                 FROM: MetalMage   09/12/2005 S# 469\nJeff Stone has posted the basic listings for Sea Strike and Hangman on his web space.  For details, see the forum on the Q-Link web site.\n\nSo, the games are in basic are they?  This means that NEW games, such as POKER or BLACK JACK could be developed, and added to the Q-Link v4 disk using ADDGAME, just like the Four in a Row, Reversi, and other game modules.\n\nThe server is a stateless environment, and game data cannot be persistant, unless Jim modifies the server to do so for a game.  However, the game client software could save game session data in memory, for game sessions.  The data is lost when the game ends and the player exits to the Lobby.  But, someone could start learning how to write new games from the old game listings.\n\nI propose BLACK JACK, two players against the dealer, or up to four players per each game session (TABLE) that may join.  That is the goal.\n\nBut, one must start simple.  KISS.  Keep it simple stupid.  Developers need to heed that warning when developing feature-rich applications.\n\nLETS START WITH the CARD GAME code for a game like BLACK JACK or POKER, for only one player vs. the computer or something... then add the two player version... and finally the four player version... unless, Jim knows how to start off someone like Jeff Stone on how to create the network version of the game.\n\nBasically, a multi-player game client would have to keep track of who is playing and who''s turn it is.  The person who sent the invite would probabaly have the game client on their side acting as the game server for the session.  Other clients would wait until the key was sent to change the state of their game client for their turn.\n\nIf someone makes the skeleton application for starting a game, and waiting for players to join, then allowing each player to end the turn, to allow the next player to take his turn, that would be the best development tool ever for this project.\n\nJim could develop the server. The Q-Linkers could develop the content to utilize the server.\n\nWhat is needed is a detailed explanation on how the two games work that we have listings for now.\n\nThink of the process as writing Java applets that connect to a server, allowing people to play a game in a multi-player network environment.\n\nMy two cents to add content.\n\n - METAL MAGE\n   dave@w3productions.com\n ');
