INSERT INTO `messages` VALUES (82, 492, 0, 409, 'BBS Server Connectivity', 'The Icon', '2005-09-18 03:25:09', 2, 'SUBJ: BBS Server Connectivity          FROM: The Icon    09/18/2005 S# 492\nThis is somewhat off the topic of Q-Link, but it is similar in the concept.\n\nI run an IMAGE BBS on a C-64 using TCPSER.  I thought it would be an interesting and challenging project to write a server in java that could accept telnet connections (calls) from the BBS.  TCPSER allows you to bind an IP/domain address to a phone number, such as 5551212.  The BBS could load a +.JC program that issues ATDT5551212 to the modem and call the server to connect for a session.\n\nFor the test, a helloworld approach would be taken to develop a protocol that is stable and flexible.\n\nFor now, I have my server running on port 6969 at w3productions.com which accepts incoming connections and starts the echo server protocol, which simply echos text received from a client back to that client until BYE is received.  That terminates the session and disconnects the client from the server.\nIt also allows the client to receive the BYE echoed text, which tells it to disconnect and reinitialize the BBS waiting for caller screen.\n\nIf the protocol is developed and the +.JC plus file for image is created to communicate with the server, the following could be implemented...\n\nLogMail.  The BBS connects and sends the daily caller activity log to the server to be logged into the MySQL database.  PHP/MySQL apps to access the data from MySQL with a browser could be developed as a tool.\n\nSMTPMail.  The BBS connects and sends messages to send via SMTP to the server.  The server then connects to the SMTP server to send the message to the intended recipient.  A special program called +.IM could be created for creating new internet e-mail messages.\n\nThe BBS could interface with MySQL via the server/DB connection for other possible applications.\n\nAnyway, Jim could probably help PHEAD, A1IEN, and I create the protocol for the server.\n\nI might have to implement the X-MODEM protocol on the java server to send/receive files to/from the BBS.\n\nIf you are familiar with IMAGE, PLUS-FILES, and the +.MODEM file for IMAGE 1.2 BBS, and you are interested, please reply.\n\nI have JDBC/MySQL connectivity supported on the server already and I have also created a SMTP mail client thread that sends a message to someone via the SMTP mail server I am running.\n\nHowever, I am pretty lost when it comes to BASIC 2.0 spaghetti code for IMAGE BBS +.FILES.\n ');
INSERT INTO `messages` VALUES (83, 493, 488, 409, 'I am back home.', 'RaymondD2', '2005-09-18 14:55:34', 0, 'SUBJ: I am back home.                  FROM: RaymondD2   09/18/2005 S# 493\nThe Expo was good! I guess a 1/3 of it was people just talking to each other. The reset was demos.\n\nThe only thing new I seen was Jeri''s new wheel like game. It has a DTV in it but this DTV has more RAM and Flashram. With only one driving game. She said it will be on Amazon.com and Raido Shack. She did not do any demo there.\n\nIt was nice to see all the people. After most of us went out and ate and talked more.\n\nI had a hard time driving home. I drove some and found a place to park and got a little sleep. Driving home at like 3am my time I was missing truns and it''s hard to get back on the right road and this was all at night. I had a GPS with me at lest I could see what way I should go. About a hour before I got home I parked and got about a nother hour sleep. I got all the way home and got more sleep at home.\n\nI set up this commodore 64c up 1st because I had my RAMLink with me. Wow it stayed backed up with the battery! That was going there about 5 hours. It was charging up there. But comming back it was about 18 hours I think. It backs it up good.\n\nWell it was real fun there. The hard part was driving back home. More then a 4 hour drive for me. Going the wrong turns last night made it over 5 hours :(\n\n-Raymond Day ');
