INSERT INTO `messages` VALUES (97, 510, 504, 409, 'Here''s who did it.', 'WiggleWorm', '2005-09-23 05:27:46', 0, 'SUBJ: Here''s who did it.               FROM: WiggleWorm  09/23/2005 S# 510\nThe good job is from Jim Brain and Keith Henrickson.\n\nThey both worked on this but by them selfs did not get a lot done. Keith got past the 9 screen main menu by using VICE and it''s monitor sending 2 letter commands that are all listed some place in the Q-Link disk. So he was "reverse engineering the Q-Link protocal"\n\nJim started it and thought it would be a challenge. He could not get to fare. Jim never got past the 9 screen menu you see at first.\n\nKeith found the message board at:\n\n8bit TelBBS - Qlink Rebuilding Project\n\nWhen they got together it took off.\n\nI found a old data file I saved from all the Q-Link data comming from the Q-link server. 7 files I named "Q BUFFER 1" to "Q BUFFER 7" That helped Jim a lot finding the 2 letter commands and packet size Q-Link used.\n\nLots of other people helped to remembering how Q-Link worked.\n\nNow Jim is working on bring back Q-Link how it was in his spair time. He has a real job, and a family too.\n\n-Raymond Day ');
INSERT INTO `messages` VALUES (98, 511, 0, 409, 'Protocol Info?', 'Madcrow64', '2005-09-26 07:32:32', 2, 'SUBJ: Protocol Info?                   FROM: Madcrow64   09/26/2005 S# 511\nI was just wondering when the info about the qlink protocol is going to be realeased to allow people start coding fallback clients for platforms not graced by VICE...\n\nMadcrow ');
INSERT INTO `messages` VALUES (99, 512, 511, 409, 'Q-Link things VICE is C64', 'RaymondD2', '2005-09-27 08:58:41', 0, 'SUBJ: Q-Link things VICE is C64        FROM: RaymondD2   09/27/2005 S# 512\nIt''s not just VICE. All you have to do is get some thing that the Q-Link disk thinks it''s working on a real 64 with a modem. VICE can do this. The mean part is the modem making Q-Link think it has a modem when it''s just using your Ethernet connection. I guess other type programs on other systems don''t have that.\n\nFor the Xbox if you have a mod chip in it you can load a commdore 64 in it. But from what I know it don''t support the modem port.\n\nSo you don''t need the Q-Link code just something that the code sees as a real commodore 64.\n\n-Raymond Day ');
INSERT INTO `messages` VALUES (100, 513, 492, 409, 'Progress', 'The Icon', '2005-09-27 09:20:30', 0, 'SUBJ: Progress                         FROM: The Icon    09/27/2005 S# 513\nI figured out that I could either use a gosub routine to translate PETSCII to ASCII in an$, which is built into IMAGE, or I could use my own translation table, and write my own routine to convert each char in the string to be sent to ASCII.  I will probably use the first method.\n\nNext, I was able to read some text from the server using get#131, an$.  But, the program is not reading ALL of the text sent and displaying it correctly.\n\nThe protocol is very simple.\n\nProgram dials 5551212 and tcpser binds that to w3productions.com 6969\n\nConnection is made and HELO is sent by the server to the program\n\nProgram sends XR to server and server responds with OK.\n\nProgram sends XS to server and server responds with OK\n\nProgram sends BYE to server and connection is closed.\n\nI am not getting the following from the server from the RS-232 port...\n\nHELO\nOK\nOK\n\nAny ideas?  I am getting a 6 instead.\n\n -- MM\n  ');
